eo-nondefault\"><span class=\"geo-dms\" title=\"Maps, aerial photos, and other data for this location\"><span class=\"latitude\">50\u00b051\u203238\u2033N</span> <span class=\"longitude\">5\u00b051\u203220\u2033E</span></span></span><span class=\"geo-multi-punct\">&#xfeff; / &#xfeff;</span><span class=\"geo-default\"><span class=\"geo-dec\" title=\"Maps, aerial photos, and other data for this location\">50.860692\u00b0N 5.855542\u00b0E</span><span style=\"display:none\">&#xfeff; / <span class=\"geo\">50.860692; 5.855542</span></span></span></a></span></span></span></td></tr><tr class=\"note\"><th scope=\"row\">Completed</th><td>\n1688</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Designations</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Rijksmonument\" title=\"Rijksmonument\">Monument</a> (1967-present)<br /><a href=\"/wiki/Hermitage_(religious_retreat)\" title=\"Hermitage (religious retreat)\">Hermitage</a> (1688-1930)</td></tr><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;background-color:#ededed\">References</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.kerkgebouwen-in-limburg.nl/kerken/schin-op-geul/kluis-op-de-schaesberg\">Church buildings in Limburg</a></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:KloesSjaatsbergwkped05.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cc/KloesSjaatsbergwkped05.JPG/220px-KloesSjaatsbergwkped05.JPG\" width=\"220\" height=\"158\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cc/KloesSjaatsbergwkped05.JPG/330px-KloesSjaatsbergwkped05.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cc/KloesSjaatsbergwkped05.JPG/440px-KloesSjaatsbergwkped05.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"598\" data-file-height=\"429\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:KloesSjaatsbergwkped05.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>The chapel in 2005</div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Exterieur_KRUISWEG_STATIE_XIV_-_Schin_op_Geul_-_20284100_-_RCE.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Exterieur_KRUISWEG_STATIE_XIV_-_Schin_op_Geul_-_20284100_-_RCE.jpg/220px-Exterieur_KRUISWEG_STATIE_XIV_-_Schin_op_Geul_-_20284100_-_RCE.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"221\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Exterieur_KRUISWEG_STATIE_XIV_-_Schin_op_Geul_-_20284100_-_RCE.jpg/330px-Exterieur_KRUISWEG_STATIE_XIV_-_Schin_op_Geul_-_20284100_-_RCE.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Exterieur_KRUISWEG_STATIE_XIV_-_Schin_op_Geul_-_20284100_-_RCE.jpg/440px-Exterieur_KRUISWEG_STATIE_XIV_-_Schin_op_Geul_-_20284100_-_RCE.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1192\" data-file-height=\"1200\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Exterieur_KRUISWEG_STATIE_XIV_-_Schin_op_Geul_-_20284100_-_RCE.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>The stations of the cross form a circle, surrounding a central shrine</div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Oud-Valkenburg-Drie_Beeldjes-2.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Oud-Valkenburg-Drie_Beeldjes-2.JPG/220px-Oud-Valkenburg-Drie_Beeldjes-2.JPG\" width=\"220\" height=\"165\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Oud-Valkenburg-Drie_Beeldjes-2.JPG/330px-Oud-Valkenburg-Drie_Beeldjes-2.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Oud-Valkenburg-Drie_Beeldjes-2.JPG/440px-Oud-Valkenburg-Drie_Beeldjes-2.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"2560\" data-file-height=\"1920\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Oud-Valkenburg-Drie_Beeldjes-2.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>The three statues on the bottom of the Schaesberg hill</div></div></div>\n<p>The <b>hermitage at Schaelsberg</b> (<a href=\"/wiki/Dutch_language\" title=\"Dutch language\">Dutch</a>: <i>kluis op de Schaelsberg</i>, <a href=\"/wiki/Limburgish_language\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Limburgish language\">Limburgish</a>: <i>kloes op de Sjaatsberg</i>) is a monumental <a href=\"/wiki/Hermitage_(religious_retreat)\" title=\"Hermitage (religious retreat)\">hermitage</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Schin_op_Geul\" title=\"Schin op Geul\">Schin op Geul</a>, in the municipality of <a href=\"/wiki/Valkenburg_aan_de_Geul\" title=\"Valkenburg aan de Geul\">Valkenburg aan de Geul</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Netherlands\" title=\"Netherlands\">Netherlands</a>. Build in 1688 for the lords of nearby <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Castle_Schaloen&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Castle Schaloen (page does not exist)\">castle Schaloen</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/Chapel\" title=\"Chapel\">chapel</a> and attached living space, housed a succession of 16 hermits from its foundation until 1930. The chapel and nearby <a href=\"/wiki/Stations_of_the_cross\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Stations of the cross\">stations of the cross</a>, added in 1843, are a <a href=\"/wiki/Rijksmonument\" title=\"Rijksmonument\">national monument</a>. Since 1758 a yearly procession, the <i>Sjaasbergergank</i>, is held to the hermitage, and this procession is listed as national <a href=\"/wiki/Intangible_cultural_heritage\" title=\"Intangible cultural heritage\">intangible cultural heritage</a>. Located in a tourist area of <a href=\"/wiki/South_Limburg_(Netherlands)\" title=\"South Limburg (Netherlands)\">South Limburg</a>, it is a popular tourist attraction.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Description\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Description</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Monument\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Monument</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#List_of_hermits\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">List of hermits</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Description\">Description</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hermitage_at_Schaelsberg&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Description\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The hermitage is located on top of the Schaesberg hill, on the edge of the <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Schaelsbergerforest&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Schaelsbergerforest (page does not exist)\">Schaelsbergerforest</a>. It is a <a href=\"/wiki/Rectangle\" title=\"Rectangle\">rectangular</a> chapel, with a small living space attached, all made out of white painted <a href=\"/wiki/Marl\" title=\"Marl\">marl</a>. The chapel has a <a href=\"/wiki/Crow-stepped_gable\" title=\"Crow-stepped gable\">crow-stepped gable</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Fl%C3%A8che\" title=\"Fl\u00e8che\">fl\u00e8che</a>, with on the north side a <a href=\"/wiki/Choir_(architecture)\" title=\"Choir (architecture)\">choir</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Apse\" title=\"Apse\">apse</a>, and on the south side a <a href=\"/wiki/Nave\" title=\"Nave\">nave</a>. Attached is a small living space, consisting of two rooms, with an upper floor and a basement. The lowest of these two rooms dates from the 15th century and was originally a hunting house of <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Castle_Schaloen&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Castle Schaloen (page does not exist)\">castle Schaloen</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-church_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-church-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>East of the chapel are <a href=\"/wiki/Stations_of_the_cross\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Stations of the cross\">stations of the cross</a>, build in 1843. The stations are presented by 14 marl pedestals, each with a <a href=\"/wiki/Niche_(architecture)\" title=\"Niche (architecture)\">niche</a> containing a <a href=\"/wiki/Lithography\" title=\"Lithography\">lithograph</a> image behind glass, all grouped in a circle surrounding a central shrine, which represents a symbolic grave, with on top the <a href=\"/wiki/Arma_Christi\" title=\"Arma Christi\">Arma Christi</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-church_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-church-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-kluis_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-kluis-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>On the bottom of the Schaesberg hill, near a bridge across the river <a href=\"/wiki/Geul\" title=\"Geul\">Geul</a> to castle Schaloen, there are three small chapels dating from 1739, dedicated to saint <a href=\"/wiki/Saint_Roch\" title=\"Saint Roch\">Roch</a>. The central chapel has a cross on top with a statue representing <a href=\"/wiki/Jesus\" title=\"Jesus\">Jesus</a>, while the outside chapels each have a statue on top, representing <a href=\"/wiki/Mary_(mother_of_Jesus)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mary (mother of Jesus)\">Mary</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/John_the_Baptist\" title=\"John the Baptist\">John the Baptist</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-kluis_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-kluis-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hermitage_at_Schaelsberg&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The chapel was dedicated to saint <a href=\"/wiki/Anthony_of_Padua\" title=\"Anthony of Padua\">Anthony of Padua</a> in 1688 and was part of the saint Mauritius <a href=\"/wiki/Parish_(Catholic_Church)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Parish (Catholic Church)\">parish</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Schin_op_Geul\" title=\"Schin op Geul\">Schin op Geul</a>. From 1688 until 1930 a succession of 16 <a href=\"/wiki/Franciscan\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Franciscan\">Franciscan</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Carthusians\" title=\"Carthusians\">Carthusian</a> hermits lived in the hermitage. \n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Monument\">Monument</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hermitage_at_Schaelsberg&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Monument\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The chapel and nearby stations of the cross have been a <a href=\"/wiki/Rijksmonument\" title=\"Rijksmonument\">national monument</a> since 14 March 1967.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Register_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Register-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> It has a sign stating it is a monument of the province of <a href=\"/wiki/Limburg_(Netherlands)\" title=\"Limburg (Netherlands)\">Limburg</a>. The province of Limburg officially does not have listed buildings, but it gives these signs to national monuments that get provincial financial support.<sup id=\"cite_ref-monumentennl_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-monumentennl-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> The area is property of <a href=\"/wiki/Vereniging_Natuurmonumenten\" title=\"Vereniging Natuurmonumenten\">Vereniging Natuurmonumenten</a> and maintained by the <i>Sjaasbergergank foundation</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-kluis_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-kluis-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>On the last Sunday of June a procession is held, the <i>Sjaasbergergank</i>. This procession is listed as national <a href=\"/wiki/Intangible_cultural_heritage\" title=\"Intangible cultural heritage\">intangible cultural heritage</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-immaterieelerfgoed_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-immaterieelerfgoed-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"List_of_hermits\">List of hermits</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hermitage_at_Schaelsberg&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: List of hermits\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>This is a list of all 16 hermits from 1688 until the last hermit died in 1930.<sup id=\"cite_ref-kluis_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-kluis-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<ul><li>Lourens Ploemen, 27 April 1688</li>\n<li>Johannes Louens</li>\n<li>Johannes Esken</li>\n<li>Benedictus Martens, 1727</li>\n<li>Arnold Haesen</li>\n<li>Petrus Prickartz, 1764</li>\n<li>Henri de Lidt, 1779</li>\n<li>Petrus Haenen, 1779</li>\n<li>Johannus Jacobs, 2 May 1816</li>\n<li>Johannes Smitsmans, 19 March 1831</li>\n<li>Peter Jozef Dresen, 1874</li>\n<li>Henricus Weerts, 4 October 1860</li>\n<li>Nicolaas Laurent, Juli 1889</li>\n<li>Clemens Salingr\u00e9, 1 December 1892</li>\n<li>Auguste Tevesen, 2 December 1906</li>\n<li>Broeder Lutgerus